div.h3: users Table PostgreSQL Row & Index Memory Layout
Why UUID over SERIAL for id
div.p: Verdict: 16-byte UUID provides essential obfuscation of business metrics and prevents IDOR enumeration.
TOAST Threshold: 2 KB email and password_hash stay inline if row < 2KB. Prevents secondary I/O lookups for login credentials.

HeapTupleHeader Offset: +00 | Size: 23B
t_xmin, t_xmax, t_cid, t_ctid Fixed system metadata for MVCC

NULL Bitmap Offset: +23 | Size: 1B
Padding/Bitmap for NULL fields

id (UUID) Offset: +24 | Size: 16B
gen_random_uuid() 128-bit Binary representation

email (TEXT) Offset: +40 | Size: 4B+Var
Varlena header (4B) + Content UNIQUE NOT NULL

password_hash (TEXT) Offset: Dynamic | Size: 64B
bcrypt (60B) + varlena (4B) Inline storage (< 2KB)

created_at (TIMESTAMPTZ) Offset: Dynamic | Size: 8B
64-bit int (s since PG epoch)

Alignment Padding Offset: End | Size: ~Var
Aligns row to 8-byte boundary

PRIMARY KEY (id) B-tree Leaf Entry
UUID(16B) + CTID(6B) Size: 22B

UNIQUE INDEX (email) B-tree Leaf Entry
Email(Var) + CTID(6B) Avg Size: ~36B
